INSERT INTO `ba_chat` VALUES ('4969', '0', '游客183', 'Malte,\n\n            Please find attached a spreadsheet of the limits for each boom configuration that define the working envelope for each mode or platform capacity condition. The definition of boom extension is the pin-to-pin dimension on the main telescopic boom. The distance of 796” represents the telescopic boom at full extension and the distance of 325” represents the boom fully retracted (as in the case of rearward analysis).\n\n  You will see that the Riser Boom can elevate to an angle of 70 degrees when in the Telescopic mode but is restricted to 60 degrees in the Articulated mode. When in the Articulated mode (where the booms can be operated independently of each other) the Main boom angle can elevate unrestricted up to its mechanical maximum of 70 degrees irrespective of the Riser boom angle.\n\n  It is desirable to limit the angle of either the Main boom or Riser boom to 1 degree less than the mechanical limit such that there is not the bump when reaching the mechanical end of stroke. A similar stop of 2 inches short of the mechanical maximum is desirable on the Telescopic boom extension also to avoid the mechanical bump at end of stroke both on extension and retraction.\n\n \n\n    In considering the conditions under which the machine will ‘accept’ the change from one mode to another this is proposed:\n\nSwitching from Telescopic to Articulated can be done at any time provided:\nThe Riser boom is below 60 degrees\nThe Telescopic boom extension is less than the distance allowed for the 900 lbs capacity choice e.g under 492” when on substantially flat ground.\nSwitching from Articulated to Telescopic mode can be done at anytime provided:\nThe two booms Riser and Main boom are within 5 degrees of synchronized\nThe Telescopic boom extension is less than the distance allowed for the 900 lbs capacity choice e.g under 708” when on substantially flat ground.\nIf you physically switch from one mode to another but the conditions are outside of those above, then the alarm should beep intermittently at a slow frequency (maybe one short beep every 1 second) and only allow functions that enable the booms to come into the conditions of the desired mode. Once these conditions are met the alarm beep will stop. Until these conditions are met the machine will continue to remain in the mode to which the boom configuration complies.\n\n \n\n  If any sensors were to fail while the machine is elevated, then only boom Telescope retract will be allowed first and once this is completed then either Main boom or Riser boom lower function will be allowed. No driving will be allowed until the boom is stowed, which if the sensor that confirms stowed has failed then means no driving.\n\n  \n\n   If the axles are within 1.5 degrees of planar to each other then elevated driving is allowed. If they are not, then elevated drive is prohibited. The axles can be beyond this out of planar requirement and the machine remain stationary for elevated platform operation. To auto level the frame levelling function the machine must be in the stowed condition. Once out of the stowed condition both axles remain locked. When in the stowed condition the front axle (furthest from the platform when driving forwards) will be un-locked and allowed to float. There is a pressure switch in the hydraulic pilot line that monitors this.\n\n \n\nAs you can see each stability configuration studied in the spreadsheet considered the angle to which the axle is tilted relative to the horizon. Please use the greater of the two axle sensor signals to determine the boom extension allowed. The machine will have an additional CAN Tilt sensor in the chassis (beyond the one on each axle) that will signal the condition of the chassis relative to the horizon. If this is beyond 3 degrees then elevated boom operation is not allowed. If the machine drives from a substantially flat situation to situation that causes the chassis to exceed 3 degrees in any plane, then driving is stopped, the tilt alarm is sounded and the sequence of Telescope boom retract and then Main boom or Riser boom lowering is allowed. This 3 degree restriction is not applied when the boom is in the stowed condition.\n\n \n\n  I think that this covers most questions but please ask as you come across conditions to be defined. I realize that the sample machine you are building does not have two oscillating axle and the frame levelling but this is to give information to the control system Engineers of the version that we are building at MEC.  \n\n \n\n  Best Regards, Gary\n\n \n\nP.S There are two booms on this machine, the Riser boom and then the Main boom which is also called the Telescopic boom.', '17', '1683072441650183', 'gpt-3.5-turbo-0301', null, null, '1683073009');
