INSERT INTO `ba_chat` VALUES ('14424', '0', 'AI机器人', 'Possible text:\n\nTransport, homeostasis and oxidation of transition metal ions beyond Cu: implications for neurodegenerative diseases\n\nCopper is a redox-active metal ion that plays diverse roles in biology and has been linked to neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer\'s, Parkinson\'s and prion diseases. However, other transition metals such as iron, zinc and manganese also have essential and potentially toxic functions in the brain, and their dysregulation may contribute to neurodegeneration. In this review, we discuss some proteins that are involved in the transport, homeostasis and oxidation of these transition metal ions and their potential relevance to neurodegenerative diseases.\n\nIron is a critical cofactor of many enzymes and proteins, including cytochrome c oxidase, aconitase, and transferrin and lactoferrin, which transport iron into and out of cells and buffer its toxicity. However, excess iron can catalyze the formation of reactive oxygen species and damage lipids, proteins and DNA in neurons. Two proteins that regulate iron export are ferroportin and ceruloplasmin. Ferroportin is a transmembrane protein that transports iron from cells to plasma, whereas ceruloplasmin is a multicopper oxidase that catalyzes the oxidation and incorporation of Fe(II) into transferrin. Mutations in ferroportin and ceruloplasmin have been associated with the iron overload disorder hereditary hemochromatosis and the neurodegenerative condition aceruloplasminemia, respectively. Studies have also suggested that iron accumulation in the brain may contribute to the pathogenesis of Alzheimer\'s and Parkinson\'s diseases.\n\nZinc is another transition metal ion that modulates neuronal function and plasticity through its coordination with receptors and enzymes such as NMDA, AMPA and metallothioneins. Zinc can be released from synaptic vesicles in response to depolarization and regulate the activity of ion channels and signal transduction pathways. However, excessive zinc can also cause oxidative stress and neurotoxicity. One protein that sequesters zinc in the cytosol and lysosomes is ZnT3, a transmembrane transporter that concentrates zinc in synaptic vesicles. Alternatively, MTs are small, cysteine-rich proteins that bind zinc and other metals with high affinity and protect cells from oxidative damage. Mutations in ZnT3 and MTs have been associated with hippocampal dysfunction and cognitive deficits in animal models and humans.\n\nManganese is a metal ion that is involved in the metabolism of amino acids, lipid peroxidation, and antioxidant defense. Manganese superoxide dismutase (SOD2) is a mitochondrial enzyme that scavenges superoxide radicals and protects against oxidative stress. However, excessive manganese exposure, as seen in occupational or environmental settings, can lead to neurotoxicity and Parkinsonism. One protein that regulates manganese transport and excretion is SLC30A10, a member of the ZnT family that exports manganese from cells. Mutations in SLC30A10 have been associated with neurological symptoms and manganese accumulation in the liver and brain.\n\nIn summary, transition metal ions beyond Cu can influence the pathogenesis of neurodegenerative diseases through their transport, homeostasis and oxidation by various proteins. Dysregulation of iron, zinc and manganese can lead to oxidative stress, protein aggregation, synaptic dysfunction, and cell death. Therefore, understanding the molecular mechanisms that control the metabolism of these metals in the brain may provide new targets for therapeutic intervention in neurodegenerative diseases.', '0', '0', 'gpt-3.5-turbo-0301', null, 'chat', '1683446871');
